name: Loft in Columbus · ★4.92 · 1 bedroom · 1 bed · 1 private bath
neighborhood_overview:
A historic neighborhood of beautiful victorian homes on lovely tree lined streets, located just a short walk from the downtown, the Main Library, Art Museum and Topiary Park (great for walking or jogging).
There are plenty of places to eat, drink and have fun only a few steps away ( coffee house, pizza parlor, tavern, restaurant, brewery and more.)
host_about:
My husband Eric and I are both artists, sharing studio space in our house. We have 2 daughters and 3 grandchildren, all of whom live in Columbus.  I've been a yoga teacher since 1988. I have taught at Yoga on High since it's inception in 2000 and earned my certification from Yoga Alliance of ERYT 1500 at Yoga on High. I love sharing this ancient practice with all kinds of people. I have seen it have profound effects on people's lives. It is an honor and a responsibility for which I am very grateful. 
 Eric and I have lived in this historic home for over 35 years, in what we consider the best neighborhood in the city, Olde Towne. We love sharing our home with friends and now airbnb guests. We enjoy walking in the woods, gardening, biking, kayaking, reading and, of course, practicing yoga. 
We also love to travel. We've been told we are easy guests. We like to take care of ourselves and not add unduly to our hosts workload. Car camping is a favorite vacation of ours.
 I'd say our airbnb hosting style is also casual: I try to think of anything a guest might need and supply it, so they can have a relaxed stay with us. We have maps of the neighborhood and menus for the local cafes and the bakery in a notebook in The Loft. We try to help out with rides when we can. We have a table in The Loft that is perfect for working or dining. A guest set up her sewing machine up there.
My favorite quote is from Emmanuel: "Your life is not your master, it is your child." Let us host your next visit to Columbus as you create your perfect visit.

name: Home in Columbus · ★4.98 · 2 bedrooms · 2 beds · 2.5 baths
neighborhood_overview:
Welcome to German Village, one of the most storied urban neighborhoods in the U.S. We are an energetic, eclectic mashup of modern lifestyles enjoying the best shops, restaurants and parks found anywhere, against a backdrop of historic brick streets and houses. Listed on the National Register of Historic Places since 1971. German Village is not just preserved architecture from the 1800s; it is the aggregation of more than 150 years of the stories of area people, families and businesses. Character lives on!

The house is located in the heart of the village among established tree lines, beautiful brick homes, brick streets, ironwork and brick sidewalks. It's like living in a giant park. We are on a lively corner. Next door is our local-made gift shop, The Red Stable, and Schmidt's Sausage Haus, a very popular destination restaurant and tourist attraction. There are several other restaurants, bars, shops and parks in the neighborhood.

Just north of us is downtown Colu
host_about: Hi, I'm Jeff. I live work & play in German Village and downtown Columbus! I graduated from OSU in Hospitality Management and have a small design firm in the neighborhood. My partner Stevo is from Croatia and speaks 5 languages.  Our pup is GiGi! We welcome you to enjoy our home away from home, nestled in the heart of German Village.

It's safe and laid-back with a diverse group of residents including young professionals, grad students, med students, and undergrads. Unlike the bustling mayhem of Central Campus, which is predominantly undergrads, South Campus offers a more peaceful area but does come alive on OSU Gamedays.

We're perfectly situated between the southern border of OSU Main Campus and northern border of Short North. Despite being a relatively quiet area we're only blocks from the energy and electricity of High Street. Once there, head north to experience the OSU college campus vibe, or south to experience the shops, bars, restaurants and vibrant nightlife of Short North.

name: Home in Columbus · ★4.93 · 1 bedroom · 1 bed · 1 shared bath

If you would like to eat delicious, wholesome, and interesting food, that is sourced locally, mostly organic, or has sustainable business practices for people, creatures and the planet, these are the businesses nearby that I highly recommend and want to support:

FAVORITE RESTAURANTS

host_about: I am grateful to my parents who first took me to Europe to explore the rich history there and ignited a flame to want to explore and learn more. A year volunteering to teach English in what was then Czechoslovakia opened my world to new and different ways of seeing and being in the world. University studies led me in Solo, Indonesia, and to South India with yoga and meditation with Sadhguru and the Isha Foundation to begin my inner exploration. Now,  I find myself following what I love and have been fascinated by many things, which has opened up so many opportunities and brought wonderful people into my life!  I started as a piano and theory teacher, occupational therapist, national yoga and movement instructor, Ayurvedic practitioner, motor scooter rider, and now gardener. Most of my activities now involve growing organic food in the backyard for myself, the folks in our neighborhood, with methods that are supportive of our pollinators and wildlife and eco-friendly to our planet. I love sharing my love and experience to anyone interested in it and enjoy hearing what others have experienced. I have a personal Isha yoga and meditation practice with Sadhguru who has provided me with tools that have been transformative for me living a more healthy, joyous, and vibrant life. It is a privilege to be able to have a hOMe for others to join and share in this journey.

As said on the German Village visitor's website, “What we have can't be replicated. We live this way — and protect it with great passion — because we understand that what we have is a neighborhood like no other." We couldn't agree more.

Schiller Park is a pleasant 8 minute walk from the property through some of the most charming streets in German Village, making it easy to go for a walk/run, have a picnic, bring the kids to the playground, and enjoy free performances of Shakespeare in the Park in the summertime. The park also has basketball courts and tennis courts.

name: Home in Columbus · ★4.98 · 4 bedrooms · 9 beds · 3 baths
neighborhood_overview: Old North Columbus is a neighborhood located just north of the Ohio State University in Columbus, Ohio. It was founded in 1847 where, at the time, it was a stand-alone city out of the confines of Columbus until it was incorporated into the City of Columbus in 1871. In its early years the city was a popular stagecoach stop with people traveling from Worthington to Columbus. Today Old North Columbus is popular for its local music and its unique "untouched architecture" which is reminiscent of its old roots.

name: Home in Columbus · ★4.79 · 1 bedroom · 1 bed · 1 private bath
neighborhood_overview:
Old Town East is one of the oldest neighborhoods in the city. The redevelopment of the neighborhood began about two decades ago and my street has been transformed over the last few years as more and more houses have been renovated and updated. There are also several new builds nearby on my street. The neighborhood is quiet and I know all of my neighbors. They are interesting, diverse, and super-friendly people.

Parts of the neighborhood are still transitioning and this is clear on a couple of streets that most GPS mapping programs will take you down when you exit I-70 or I-71. The area around my home is safe and well maintained. I encourage visitors to use the Broad Street Exit near downtown as an alternative - it won't add any time on to your trip. As you head east down Broad Street you'll see some amazingly restored historic houses as well as Franklin Park, which is beautiful and perfect for running, walking, and exploring.

name: Home in Columbus · ★4.85 · 1 bedroom · 1 bed · 1 shared bath
neighborhood_overview:
Our neighborhood, Clintonville, is one of C-bus’ jewels. Just north of the University area, the neighborhood is full of vintage homes, built between 1900 and the 1930s. Always in the top 3 of best places to live and hang out in Columbus, it’s progressive, walkable, and safe. Clintonville has lots of restaurants, breweries, coffee shops, and bars, along with shops of all kinds, many of which are within a few block walk of our home. Our home is exactly halfway between High St, with all the stops and places to eat and drink, and the Olentangy Bike Trail, which takes you from downtown to the south, to Worthington, a few miles to the north, and several parks along the way.

High St is Columbus’ main thoroughfare, and it can take you pretty much anywhere you need to go. Busses are frequent and inexpensive, and Uber or Lyft can take you downtown, OSU, or the Short North in just a few minutes.

name: Home in Columbus · ★4.90 · 2 bedrooms · 2 beds · 1.5 baths
neighborhood_overview:
Stretching north from Ohio State to Worthington, Clintonville is a large neighborhood with many attractions, from the Park of Roses to the independently owned retail shops and restaurants that line High Street. Standout shops include modern decor purveyor Elm and Iron, fabric mecca Sew to Speak and all-locally made Wholly Craft.

During warmer months, people flock to the Clintonville Farmers Market to get fresh produce and to the Olentangy River recreational trail to hike and bike. Arts venues like Wild Goose Creative and Studio 35 provide cultural opportunities year-round.

Start your day with a cup of coffee at Cup O' Joe or Crimson Cup, both on the Columbus Coffee Trail. Dining choices veer toward farm-to-table, with Acre, Harvest Pizzeria, The Crest Gastropub and Angry Bear Kitchen as standouts. Get in line for world-class barbecue at the Ray Ray’s Hog Pit truck, at live music hotspot Ace of Cups.

name: Cottage in Columbus · ★4.93 · 2 bedrooms · 3 beds · 1 bath
neighborhood_overview:
German Village is a historic neighborhood just south of downtown Columbus, OH. Initially platted in 1814 in Columbus' South End, German Village was generally developed between years 1840 and 1914. It was settled largely by German immigrants in the mid-1800s. German descendants at one time comprised as much as one-third of the population of Columbus. Restoration began in 1959 and the Historic District was established in 1963. German Village was the FIRST historic district in the U.S. and it remains a model for all that came after. In the year 1974, German Village joined the Historic Register. Today, more than 1,600 preservations have been completed.

Purdy Haus dates to at least the year 1910 when it was occupied by a woodworker/barber George C. McMillin. Nearby homes date between years 1884 and 1888, so it may be older.

Walk everywhere - sidewalks are wide - people are warm - parks and restaurants are plentiful! And German Village is central to everything

name: Home in Columbus · ★4.98 · 2 bedrooms · 2 beds · 1 bath
neighborhood_overview:
This is a quiet single family home neighborhood. Several restaurants nearby along High Street, North and South.

Clintonville is a great place to live and is in the perfect location. Close enough to downtown Columbus to go whenever you want, yet you still feel like you are in your own neighborhood apart from the rest. There are many things to do and see. High street has many cool, quirky, unique shops and restaurants. The people are open-minded, welcoming, and kind; which gives Clintonville that community feeling. When the tight knit community becomes too much, you can take a quick trip into downtown Columbus, the Short North, or pretty much any other part of Columbus, because Clintonville is right in the center of it.
host_about:
We live in Clintonville and have three cats and two dogs.  We live and work in the community. As the hosts of Wincott Place we want our guests to feel comfortable and at home when they stay with us.  

Having stayed on friend's couches, in numerous hotel rooms, BNB's, and Airbnb the conversation has always centered on what would we do differently as a host.  From having a throw blanket for lounging on the couch, that certain kitchen tool, green space outside,  to having games available to play as a group or family. 

We try to be mindful of the earth and conservation. Our rental has general recycling available for our guests. If you are not sure if something can be recycled, leave it for us and we will make the decision for you. We also compost food. Leave us your leftovers (and scrap remnants if you like) in the refrigerator. The local composting company we work with that will even take meat and bones. 

Each of our animals has their own distinct personalities that make us smile and want to give them a hug.  This does not mean that everyone else does though. We each have several family members with pet allergies so we want there to be somewhere that is pet free, has items in it that have not been in contact with animals, like Wincott Place, to keep allergies at bay.

neighborhood_overview:
German Village is a vibrant place to stay, shop, and play. Walking the brick sidewalks, you'll discover a neighborhood full of urban gardens, beautiful historic homes built over 100 years ago, and carefully dispersed small businesses. As said on the German Village visitor's website, “What we have can't be replicated. We live this way — and protect it with great passion — because we understand that what we have is a neighborhood like no other." We couldn't agree more.

Schiller Park is a pleasant 8 minute walk from the property through some of the most charming streets in German Village, making it easy to go for a walk/run, have a picnic, bring the kids to the playground, and enjoy free performances of Shakespeare in the Park in the summertime. The park also has basketball courts and tennis courts.

Another one of our favorite parks is Scioto Audubon Metro Park, which is located .8 miles from the house. The park has a large rock climbing wall, walking paths (both

name: Condo in Columbus · ★4.84 · 1 bedroom · 1 bed · 1 bath
neighborhood_overview: The Short North has been described as "colorful", "offbeat", and "trendy". The district is heavily populated with art galleries, specialty shops, pubs, nightclubs, and coffee houses. Most of its tightly packed brick buildings date from at least the early 20th century, with traditional storefronts along High Street (often with brightly painted murals on their side walls), and old apartment buildings and rowhouses and newer condominium developments in the surrounding blocks. The city installed 17 lighted metal archways extending across High Street throughout the Short North, reminiscent of such arches present in the area in the early 1900s.

Known as the art and soul of Columbus, the culturally rich Short North Arts District is a pioneer in the urban revitalization of Central Ohio. Visitors are invited to explore our vibrant neighborhood known for its wide variety of amazing art, dining, nightlife, fashion, home décor, and unique gifts.

The Short North Arts District sits along the stretch of High Street between downtown and Ohio State’s campus and is signified by the 17 lighted arches that line the main thoroughfare. At its heart, the Short North is an arts neighborhood, as evidenced by the many murals along the sides of the buildings. Beyond that, it’s a hub of activity offering more than 100 restaurants, galleries and boutiques and booming with new mixed-use and residential development.

I’m a moderately geeky real estate investor who prefers to be outdoors and is an avid hiker, fisher, runner and explorer. 

I live in one of my favorite places, Columbus, Ohio.  I moved here from NYC in 2014.

At Edifice, we algorithmically analyze and acquire foreclosures in qualified opportunity zones and develop those properties into vacation rentals that double as live-action guest experiences.  We work to reconceptualize residential real estate and the hotel industry, offering you the opportunity to book your own fantasy world.  Our primary goal is your satisfactory suspension of disbelief.  

We encourage you to raise the question:  why stay in a hotel room when I could otherwise rule from the pinnacles of King's Landing or Caesar's Palace, escape 1,000 leagues under the sea, wage my own wizard battle, establish a new dynasty at Pi-Ramesses, lead my lion pack into the Serengeti, cross swords with Hook in my pirate fortress, or cast down dragons in my own lair?  

I love great food and cocktails and am full of suggestions for fulfilling local experiences.  I also love animals.  I own cats and grew up with dogs.   I design my homes to be pet friendly and would love to meet your pets.  After all, your pets will be jealous if you fail to include them in your fantasy adventure.

We are always looking for new ideas, suggestions and guidance regarding our existing properties and ideas for future worlds.  Your assistance is commendable.

We understand that the true cost of a hotel includes the opportunity cost of your time and promise to work diligently to maximize your enjoyment from every second of your vacation adventure.  You'll never again be comfortable sitting on your bed at the Hilton watching infomercials.  Game on, Paris.

I enjoy a good conversation over a glass of wine. As hosts, we are friendly but will give you all the space you need.

name: Home in Columbus · ★4.82 · 1 bedroom · 1 bed · 1 shared bath
neighborhood_overview:
My neighborhood was at one place the homes of James Thurber and the Robber Barons of old. It is gorgeous with a variety of old homes--Queen Anne, Victorian--and tree lined streets. It is experiencing a renaissance and offers a tavern (very good food!), a diner where you can enjoy a good breakfast, a pizza shop that's a cut above the chain pizza's, and a new vegan cafe.
These restaurants are a 5-10 minute minute walk from the house.
host_about: I am a friendly person who enjoys getting to know others.  I love to read, work in the yard, sing, sing, sing and snuggle with my dog--when he let's me. I love tea, love Italy and enjoyed Ireland and enjoy movies shown at art cinemas. I don't watch much television but when I do it's usually PBS. I don't smoke.  I really enjoy travelling and have been on package tours and well as trips where I hunt out hostels.  I appreciate having different people around!

name: Home in Columbus · ★4.92 · 4 bedrooms · 5 beds · 3.5 baths
neighborhood_overview: The Short North Arts District is one of the Midwest’s best kept secrets. There is a huge variety of unique shops, bars and restaurants, and art galleries along High Street and a number of annual events that take place year-round. We have a thorough list of recommendations in the house to local bakeries, cafes, and restaurants.
host_about:
A few years after meeting in Japan, we moved to Columbus in 2OO9 and have been loving it ever since! We love traveling (25+ countries between us) and are passionate about renovating historic homes and building new homes. Please check out our IGs at @RoweRentals and @RoweHouseCbus to see our house journey.

We love being hosts- providing a comfortable home to travelers visiting our gem of a city- 'Cbus'! We know quite a lot about Short North entertainment & restaurants- there is so much to do here, feel free to ask!
- Ingrid, Mike, and Co-Hosts Tracy and Christine

Our life motto- Live like someone left the gate open!

name: Condo in Columbus · ★4.43 · 2 bedrooms · 2 beds · 1 bath
neighborhood_overview: Located in the revitalizing Southern Orchards neighborhood, our house enjoys a central position in a community on the rise. Explore nearby attractions like the Children's Hospital, German Village, Franklin Park Conservatory and Botanical Garden, Scioto Audubon Metro Park, Lou Berliner Sports Park, Columbus Museum of Art, and downtown Columbus. The Ohio State University Stadium is a mere 15-minute drive away, ensuring easy access to exciting events. Immerse yourself in the transformed spirit of Columbus from this prime location!
host_about:
I am an easy-going owner and take pride in all things I do. I will always do my best to make sure my guests’ stays are seamless so you can enjoy everything. Columbus, South Florida & Tahoe have to offer!

Love traveling, sports, meeting new people and most importantly love life!

name: Rental unit in Columbus · ★4.82 · 3 bedrooms · 3 beds · 1 bath
neighborhood_overview:
4th Street Bar & Grill - great for sports games, craft beer carryout til 230am! (hard to find)
Suzie Q's Pool Hall - laid back pool hall with drinks and games
Three carryouts within walking distance, one 24/7 with a gas station...also a coin-operated laundromat just a block away!
Within a few mile radius there are 3 grocery stores (Giant Eagle, Kroger, Lucky's Market) and 3 liquor stores as well.
host_about: Tall, funny guy who is super clean and easy going :)

name: Townhouse in Columbus · ★4.90 · 2 bedrooms · 3 beds · 1 bath
neighborhood_overview:
This walkable, bikeable neighborhood, a short 1.5 miles from downtown Columbus and it’s major highways, is one of Columbus’ most coveted areas. A hybrid of urban flair and neighborhood warmth, Grandview’s vibes are at the same time laid-back and buzzing with energy. Stroll the wide, tree-lined sidewalks of Grandview Ave amid the hum of cafe-table chatter.

Discover specialized independent shops, curated New-York style boutiques, a chocolatier’s gorgeous handmade truffles, independent breweries, top-rated coffee roasters, cutting-edge salons, and of course, world-class restaurants that use fresh, locally-sourced ingredients. The electric mix of restaurants here have consistently been recognized by critics and diners alike for their cuisine, ambience, and outstanding attention to detail. Grandview is also home to a collection of award-winning craft microbreweries and taprooms.

A hub of creative culture and out-of-the-ordinary experiences, Grandview offers an array
host_about:
Hello, my name is Joe - I was born and raised in Ohio and love Airbnb which means you’ll receive high service and quality, local recommendations to make the most of your trip. Feel free to instantly book or message me, I’m happy to answer any specific questions in advance.

By day, I’m a consultant. 
By night, I’m a friends/family man and an Ohio sports junkie. 

I’m a well traveled Airbnb guest and have pulled a lot of inspiration from other properties so I know what great hosts should do to create a comfortable guest experience. Be sure to ask me about a few of my favorite things on our welcome sheet.

Make yourself at home!

name: Home in Columbus · ★4.64 · 4 bedrooms · 7 beds · 2.5 baths
neighborhood_overview: Coffee shop, local bar, and convenience store within 5 minute walking distance.

name: Home in Columbus · ★4.75 · 1 bedroom · 1 bed · 2 shared baths
neighborhood_overview:
We are located to the east of Columbus. With lots of great eateries at a convenient distance such as:
• Scotty’s Cafe
• Cherbourg Bakery
• Rubino’s Pizza
• Jeni’s Splendid Ice Creams
• Stav’s Diner
• Brassica

Minutes to Columbus John Glenn Airport, 5 minutes to Easton Shopping Center, 10 minutes to Expo Center, 15 minutes to The Ohio State University/Downtown/Short North.

A little more inwards you will find Columbus’ Near East Side; an up-and-coming destination just east of downtown Columbus, beyond the Columbus Museum of Art. This collection of neighborhoods, which includes Olde Towne East, the King-Lincoln District, and Franklin Park, is an up-and-coming area full of stately Victorian homes and leafy streets. Olde Towne East is host to interesting clusters of dining and nightlife along Parsons Avenue and Oak Street. On Parsons, grab a coffee at Upper Cup, enjoy farm-fresh produce at Black Creek Bistro and music and drinks at
host_about:
Hello! 

We are Dane and Alicia (DNA), we both are world travelers with a passion for real estate and hospitality, based in Columbus OH! Considering a deep-rooted passion for anything to do with hospitality and facilitating great customer experiences, Airbnb is the perfect thing to do! 

Not only do we love being Airbnb hosts, but we also love being on the traveling spectrum too. Have traveled a lot and am now doing more overseas travel!

We really enjoy the ability to share the experience of living in this wonderful house. Definitely check with us for amazing must visit locations, where to go for superb walks and wonderful experiences in Columbus! We love meeting new people from different walks of life, but as a host, we give my guests all the space they want.

Looking forward to hosting you soon,

Dane & Alicia

name: Rental unit in Columbus · ★4.90 · 1 bedroom · 1 bed · 1 bath
neighborhood_overview: "The Victorian Village is known for quaint, leafy streets lined with late-19th- and early-20th-century homes in a variety of architectural styles, such as Gothic Revival mansions, Second Empire villas, and Queen Anne houses. Paths crisscross sprawling Goodale Park, a setting for annual music festivals. Overlooking the park, the Pizzuti Collection hosts contemporary art exhibitions and has a free sculpture garden."
host_about:
I love fixing up houses, hosting, and traveling! I'm a Realtor, home renovator, and Property Manager at Stay Awhile Hosting Co.

I’ve been an Airbnb host since 2013 when I used to live in New York City. I moved to Columbus, Ohio to restore homes and host travelers full time in 2018. When I'm not working on homes I'm playing with my two rescue pups or heading out to a great restaurant with my hubby.

name: Rental unit in Columbus · ★4.68 · 1 bedroom · 1 bed · 1 bath
neighborhood_overview:
This apartment is situated in a quiet part of High Street in Downtown Columbus. Within a block, you'll find an Irish Pub, Wine, Coffee, and Chocolate Shop, Barbeque Restaurant, Tapas Restaurant, and Hotel Restaurant. There's a European suit store directly below the apartment. Two blocks walk in either direction leads you to more restaurants, bars, arcades, and downtown parks and patios surrounded by office buildings.

(No Smoking. Please see house rules.)
host_about:
During college, I spent two years on the road as a musician, performing shows with 21 Pilots, and all around the US and Europe. Throughout my travels, I started a few small businesses and non-profits, and made Columbus my home. I’m currently a Management Consultant. I travel internationally for technology projects, speak at conferences, and research culture in city transformation initiatives.

As an AirBnB host, I enjoy creating the kind of environment that I would want to have for myself as a traveler — a place that’s modern, comfortable, equipped with new and working amenities, and in the heart of downtown, near bars, restaurants, theaters, and conferences, yet still restful and peaceful.

neighborhood_overview:
Joel’s home is located in Columbus, Ohio, United States.
Located in the beautiful Harrison West neighborhood, this home is perfectly situated in the heart of the city. Just blocks away from High Street and the Short North attractions, Ohio State's main campus, OSU Wexner Medical Center, and Grandview. host_about:
We are childhood friends and business partners.
We are originally from Canton, Ohio and now reside in the Cleveland area. We both graduated from The Ohio State University and started hosting on Airbnb in 2013. We started Cleveland House Hotels, which is a short term vacation property company in 2015.  We have a full time cleaning staff and maintenance person on hand to take care of any issues. 

Niko (Nick) has been in the hospitality business for many years, having worked in hotels and restaurants.  He owns a small diner in Old Brooklyn called Gus's Family Restaurant.  He is married and has two children.  In addition to cooking and owning a restaurant, Niko is the co-founder and COO of Cleveland House Hotels.  

Billy is a co-founder and CEO of Cleveland House Hotels.  Billy is a successful real estate investor and has been in the sales business for over 15 years.  He loves traveling and spending time with his son, William.

name: Townhouse in Columbus · ★4.87 · 1 bedroom · 1 bed · 1 bath
neighborhood_overview:
Columbus' premier downtown neighborhood and one of the preeminent historic districts in the United States. German Village is a 233-acre historic residential district.

Walking down one of the many tree-shaded, brick-lined streets of German Village in Columbus, Ohio. To either side you will see neat brick bungalows — a grander Federal or Victorian occasionally elbowing in among them — present their tidy facades and immaculate front yards!

Dozens of local shops, cafes and restaurants will keep you entertained. Truly a unique gem of a village!
host_about: I am a working professional from Ohio.    I love traveling and new experiences.

host_about:
Welcome to Columbus!  We have a lot to see and to do here. We enjoy outdoors like hiking, biking, kayaking. Our son is studying in Germany, and we love to travel. We both made a lot of friends and hope to meet more from around the Globe by hosting in our home. We believe you should treat people the way you want to be treated. With love and respect.

name: Home in Columbus · ★4.76 · 5 bedrooms · 5 beds · 2 baths
neighborhood_overview: The Old North is a quiet neighborhood near OSU. You can get to I-71 within two minutes of getting in your car, and from there to most locations in Columbus in 20 minutes or less. OSU is five minutes away and you are 15 minutes from John Glenn Columbus International Airport.
host_about:
I’m a moderately geeky real estate investor who prefers to be outdoors and is an avid hiker, fisher, runner and explorer. 

I live in one of my favorite places, Columbus, Ohio.  I moved here from NYC in 2014.

At Edifice, we algorithmically analyze and acquire foreclosures in qualified opportunity zones and develop those properties into vacation rentals that double as live-action guest experiences.  We work to reconceptualize residential real estate and the hotel industry, offering you the opportunity to book your own fantasy world.  Our primary goal is your satisfactory suspension of disbelief.  

We encourage you to raise the question:  why stay in a hotel room when I could otherwise rule from the pinnacles of King's Landing or Caesar's Palace, escape 1,000 leagues under the sea, wage my own wizard battle, establish a new dynasty at Pi-Ramesses, lead my lion pack into the Serengeti, cross swords with Hook in my pirate fortress, or cast down dragons in my own lair?  

I love great food and cocktails and am full of suggestions for fulfilling local experiences.  I also love animals.  I own cats and grew up with dogs.   I design my homes to be pet friendly and would love to meet your pets.  After all, your pets will be jealous if you fail to include them in your fantasy adventure.

We are always looking for new ideas, suggestions and guidance regarding our existing properties and ideas for future worlds.  Your assistance is commendable.

We understand that the true cost of a hotel includes the opportunity cost of your time and promise to work diligently to maximize your enjoyment from every second of your vacation adventure.  You'll never again be comfortable sitting on your bed at the Hilton watching infomercials.  Game on, Paris.

host_about:

name: Home in Columbus · ★4.98 · 3 bedrooms · 2 beds · 1.5 baths
neighborhood_overview: This is a diverse and central area, walking distance or a brief drive away from historic neighborhoods Merion and German Village. We are conveniently right off of Parsons Ave, so you may experience some, though infrequent, noise filtering in off the main road during rush hour. Since we are off of a major street, exercise basic precautions such as locking your car and bringing valuables inside with you. We have never had safety issues for our house, and our neighbors watch out for each other, but it does not hurt to be prudent in a semi-urban area! We recommend going for a walk across Parsons (west of the house) and not further down our street (to the east of us) — the former is a much better walk with things to see/do.
host_about:
I enjoy seeing cities from a local’s perspective through Airbnb when we are traveling, and hope to bring the same to our guests. My husband and I moved to Columbus in 2018 and started hosting in 2019. It’s been especially fulfilling to host families traveling for care at the nearby pediatric hospital. 

I speak French and love learning about languages and cultures.

My husband Jacob, our infant daughter, and our cat Pearl are my crew.

I love clean spaces with character & interest, but not to busy. I appreciate hosts that are available when you need them & honest about the accommodations.

name: Home in Columbus · ★4.93 · 2 bedrooms · 3 beds · 1 bath
neighborhood_overview:
You'll be staying in the Sharon Heights neighborhood - which is in Sharon Township, a very clean and quiet community, full of friendly residents who will probably smile and wave if you pass them.

You will conveniently be just north of a shopping area that contains a large Target (with Starbucks) and Kroger (grocery) stores, and several fast food locations (Noodles & Co., BIBIBOP, Bob Evans, Raising Canes, and more!)

Within walking distance, just up on the main street (High Street, which runs north thru Worthington into Delaware and south thru the Ohio State Campus and into downtown), you can catch several bus lines. There are also great Greek, BBQ, and Vietnamese restaurants in that area of High Street.
host_about: My husband Earl and I find ourselves with more time to explore places we've never been now that our two kids are (mostly) on their own.  Our travels and experiences have lead us to try hosting, too.  We've had great AirBNB experiences and strive to be the kind of hosts (when hosting) and guests (when traveling) that you are hoping for!

We are Igor, Boris and Susan - friends that are happy to open up our home to host you and your group in the wonderful city of Columbus. 

A few words about us:

Igor is a financial analyst that has been working in the industry for nearly a decade.

Boris and Susan are a young, professional couple originally from Lithuania and China. 

We all love to travel ourselves and try to stay at Airbnb wherever we go. 

Between all of us, we've been to probably over a 100 Airbnbs over the years and have seen a range from unbelievably beautiful ones to the not-so-good ones.

We wanted to share this house with Airbnb guests as a way to pay back the incredibly hospitality and experiences we've encountered ourselves during our travels. We know what it's like to come to a new place for the first time, especially if you have a group of people with you, and our goal is to provide you with a wonderful, cozy and unique place to stay and advice and feedback that you would expect from a friend.

If you need anything, we're always just a message away, so don't hesitate to reach out at any time!

name: Home in Columbus · ★4.99 · 3 bedrooms · 3 beds · 2 baths
neighborhood_overview:
Walk to coffee, shops, restaurants, ravines, and a movie theater!
Clintonville is a cute family friendly neighborhood. You’ll see its residents walking their dogs and enjoying local shops and restaurants. Walkable from the Airbnb on Indianola Ave is a group of cute shops, a gyro truck, pizza shop, record store, and a locally owned movie theater. Two nearby ravines offer beautiful nature fulled walks. The Park of Roses is a short drive away. While there enjoy a park, playground, and bike/walk path that takes you downtown. This house is located in a great location and close to everything Columbus has to offer.

neighborhood_overview:
Franklinton is one of the hottest up and coming neighbourhoods in Columbus. The thriving East Franklinton neighbourhood, which has breweries, bars, several food options, art galleries, etc., is located about a mile away. There is a coffee shop and diner within a few blocks to help get your day started, and a small market for produce and essentials.

Overall, I have felt very safe in Franklinton. The neighbors on Cypress are great and look out for each other. However, please note this is a city neighborhood near downtown Columbus. Precaution should be taken at night and valuables should not be left in your vehicle. If you are not comfortable with this, I would not recommend staying here.

name: Townhouse in Columbus · ★4.92 · 2 bedrooms · 3 beds · 1.5 baths
neighborhood_overview:
German Village is a historic neighborhood just south of downtown Columbus, OH. Initially platted in 1814 in Columbus' South End, German Village was generally developed between years 1840 and 1914. It was settled largely by German immigrants in the mid-1800s. German descendants at one time comprised as much as one-third of the population of Columbus. Restoration began in 1959 and the Historic District was established in 1963. German Village was the FIRST historic district in the U.S. and it remains a model for all that came after. In the year 1974, German Village joined the Historic Register. Today, more than 1,600 preservations have been completed.

Walk everywhere - sidewalks are wide - people are warm - parks and restaurants are plentiful! And German Village is central to everything in Columbus.

Distances to:
Nationwide Children's Hospital:
1.2 miles - Driving 7 min. - Walking 26 min.
Downtown:
1.5 miles - Driving 8 min. - Walking 32

The MAPFRE stadium is home to Columbus’ most admired Major League Soccer team the Columbus Crew! Not only is this venue used for sporting events, but it is also used for music festivals.

name: Rental unit in Columbus · ★4.96 · 2 bedrooms · 2 beds · 1 bath
neighborhood_overview: Our place is in one of the BEST area's of Columbus,Ohio. The German Village- Merion Village area is a historic Columbus community and is known for gorgeous brick streets and architecture. Historic restaurants and bars are prominent within the area and are easily accessibly from our place. There is so much to see and do and most of the area is pedestrian friendly.  Most of our favorite eateries are within a 10-15 walk or 5 minute drive including Barcelona, Brown Bag Deli, G. Michaels, Lindeys, Katzingers Deli, Pistachio Vera, The Skillet, Sycamore Cafe, Harvest Pizza and many more.      Schiller Park is the second oldest park in the City of Columbus and it is only a 5 minute walk from our place. The park is a well-kept central location of German Village life. The recreation center, picnic areas, softball diamonds, fishing pond and stage for the Actor's Summer Theater, not to mention the beautifully landscaped gardens, make Schiller Park the jewel of German Village. name: Home in Columbus · ★4.90 · 2 bedrooms · 3 beds · 1.5 baths
neighborhood_overview: Olde Towne East, as it is called today, was annexed into the city of Columbus in 1870. It had previously been an area of family operated farms and countryside stretching along the National Road, Main Street from Washington D.C. In 1882, trolley tracks were laid on Oak Street to Kelton Ave where the streetcar barn still stands, providing convenient transportation to the former location of the Ohio State Fairgrounds, (now Franklin Park Conservatory), and to downtown Columbus. Olde Towne East saw many of Columbus’s finest homes built within the area and much of that architectural legacy still exists today. There are more than a thousand uniquely styled homes in the Olde Towne East area, some built as early as 1830, representing over 50 unique architectural styles. During the late 19th and early 20th centuries, Olde Towne East represented some of the most popular American building styles spanning 100 years, which included: Federal, Italianate, Victorian, Queen Anne, Gothic Revival, Tudor.

name: Home in Columbus · ★4.85 · 4 bedrooms · 4 beds · 5 baths
neighborhood_overview:
German Village is a vibrant place to stay, shop, and play. Walking the brick sidewalks, you'll discover a neighborhood full of urban gardens, beautiful historic homes built over 100 years ago, and carefully dispersed small businesses. As said on the German Village visitor's website, “What we have can't be replicated. We live this way — and protect it with great passion — because we understand that what we have is a neighborhood like no other." We couldn't agree more.

Schiller Park is a pleasant 8 minute walk from the property through some of the most charming streets in German Village, making it easy to go for a walk/run, have a picnic, bring the kids to the playground, and enjoy free performances of Shakespeare in the Park in the summertime. The park also has basketball courts and tennis courts.

Another one of our favorite parks is Scioto Audubon Metro Park, which is located .8 miles from the house. The park has a large rock climbing wall, walking paths (both

We have been hosting since 2014 and have enjoyed sharing our homes with travelers from near & far. It’s incredibly rewarding to be a small part of our guests’ experience when they’re visiting our city.

This apartment is located in a fast-growing area of downtown with lots of exciting shops and restaurants opening all the time. It's peacefully tucked in a quieter area away from the bar scenes of The Short North while still being only 5-10 minutes drive away.

Our place is nestled along the river and perfectly located for anyone who enjoys going on walks or bike rides with the beautiful Scioto Mile trail running right behind the community.

You'll love being just a few steps away from Ray Ray's BBQ, Brewdog, One Line Coffee, Strongwater, Yellow Brick gourmet pizza, and many other favorites.

It's easy to get anywhere downtown...by car, bicycle, scooter, Uber/Lyft, walking, bus, etc.

name: Home in Columbus · ★4.71 · 2 bedrooms · 2 beds · 1 bath
neighborhood_overview:
German Village is a charming neighborhood, voted as Columbus' best neighborhood years in a row.

From the brick lined streets, to awe inspiring giant hanging pieces of art in the gem of the GV, Schiller Park with its fountains, scenic lake with ducks, Shakespeare In the Park series in the Summer, to the best of dining experiences with the premier restaurants Lindey's, Barcelona, The Mohawk to nationally recognized Thurman Cafe and Fox in Snow, to curiosities galore in gallery spaces, artisan markets, all nestled in brick structures built by German immigrants in the early 1900's.

Must sees: The Book Loft is an old mansion of 32 rooms full of books. It is like a crazy maze!

Every Saturday, there is a Farmer's Market in front of St. Mary's Church, 700 S Third , a ten minute walk from the house.

Also on Third is Pistacia Vera-- the line is long, but well worth it. The chocolate bomb is to die for.

And just around the corner on Jaeg

neighborhood_overview:

Flowers and Bread - a unique local bakery/cafe that also does flower arranging classes!

Restaurants: To many to list them all but we love Northstar Cafe, Hot Chicken Takeover, Rusty Bucket, and Local Cantina!

Other Activities: The Columbus Park of Roses - One of Columbus's largest metro parks, and a beautiful rose garden that is an icon of the area.

I’m a moderately geeky real estate investor who prefers to be outdoors and is an avid hiker, fisher, runner and explorer. 

I live in one of my favorite places, Columbus, Ohio.  I moved here from NYC in 2014.

At Edifice, we algorithmically analyze and acquire foreclosures in qualified opportunity zones and develop those properties into vacation rentals that double as live-action guest experiences.  We work to reconceptualize residential real estate and the hotel industry, offering you the opportunity to book your own fantasy world.  Our primary goal is your satisfactory suspension of disbelief.  

We encourage you to raise the question:  why stay in a hotel room when I could otherwise rule from the pinnacles of King's Landing or Caesar's Palace, escape 1,000 leagues under the sea, wage my own wizard battle, establish a new dynasty at Pi-Ramesses, lead my lion pack into the Serengeti, cross swords with Hook in my pirate fortress, or cast down dragons in my own lair?  

I love great food and cocktails and am full of suggestions for fulfilling local experiences.  I also love animals.  I own cats and grew up with dogs.   I design my homes to be pet friendly and would love to meet your pets.  After all, your pets will be jealous if you fail to include them in your fantasy adventure.

We are always looking for new ideas, suggestions and guidance regarding our existing properties and ideas for future worlds.  Your assistance is commendable.

We understand that the true cost of a hotel includes the opportunity cost of your time and promise to work diligently to maximize your enjoyment from every second of your vacation adventure.  You'll never again be comfortable sitting on your bed at the Hilton watching infomercials.  Game on, Paris.

neighborhood_overview:
Not kidding here: Clintonville was recently named the "Nicest Place in Ohio" by Reader's Digest. Here's a short excerpt from the article:

The Clintonville neighborhood in Columbus, Ohio is an older area of the city filled with a wealth of houses built in the early 1900’s, stately old trees, parks, shops, restaurants and possibly the highest density of Toyota Priuses per capita of anywhere you’ll find. The sense of community is really impressive here and our neighborhood recently gained national attention when two young aspiring musicians put on a porch recital for their 78 year old neighbor Helena Schlam while she was sheltering in place at home.

name: Cottage in Columbus · ★4.94 · 2 bedrooms · 3 beds · 1.5 baths
neighborhood_overview:
The neighborhood is safe and charming. I have owned the house for many years. There are many things to see (and eat) in the neighborhood!

If you are looking for food:

The world famous, Schmidt's Sausage Haus and Restaurant is a short 8min walk. Has all types of authentic German sausages, pretzels and pastries.

I also recommend Barcelona Restaurant & Bar, it has phenomenal ambiance and features traditionally Spanish cuisine.

The Brown Bag is located closeby on Whittier, awesome breakfast and lunch fare.

For spirited drinks and beers, here are my neighborhood favorites:

- Antiques on High - phenomenal atmosphere, sour beers and cocktails.

- Law Bird - great little wine and cocktail spot, also on High St.

Also must try Jeni's Ice Cream down the block as well, you will not be disappointed!

name: Rental unit in Columbus · 1 bedroom · 2 beds · 1 bath
Townhouse in Columbus · ★4.99 · 3 bedrooms · 3 beds · 2 baths
neighborhood_overview: This walkable, bikeable neighborhood, a short 1.5 miles from downtown Columbus and it’s major highways, is one of Columbus’ most coveted areas. A hybrid of urban flair and neighborhood warmth, Grandview’s vibes are at the same time laid-back and buzzing with energy. Stroll the wide, tree-lined sidewalks of Grandview Ave amid the hum of cafe-table chatter. Discover specialized independent shops, curated New-York style boutiques, a chocolatier’s gorgeous handmade truffles, independent breweries, top-rated coffee roasters, cutting-edge salons, and of course, world-class restaurants that use fresh, locally-sourced ingredients. The electric mix of restaurants here have consistently been recognized by critics and diners alike for their cuisine, ambience, and outstanding attention to detail. Grandview is also home to a collection of award-winning craft microbreweries and taprooms. A hub of creative culture and out-of-the-ordinary experiences, Grandview offers an array of guided food and drink

We work hard so that we can see all there is in this big wide world!

host_about:
I’m a moderately geeky real estate investor who prefers to be outdoors and is an avid hiker, fisher, runner and explorer. 

I live in one of my favorite places, Columbus, Ohio.  I moved here from NYC in 2014.

At Edifice, we algorithmically analyze and acquire foreclosures in qualified opportunity zones and develop those properties into vacation rentals that double as live-action guest experiences.  We work to reconceptualize residential real estate and the hotel industry, offering you the opportunity to book your own fantasy world.  Our primary goal is your satisfactory suspension of disbelief.  

We encourage you to raise the question:  why stay in a hotel room when I could otherwise rule from the pinnacles of King's Landing or Caesar's Palace, escape 1,000 leagues under the sea, wage my own wizard battle, establish a new dynasty at Pi-Ramesses, lead my lion pack into the Serengeti, cross swords with Hook in my pirate fortress, or cast down dragons in my own lair?  

I love great food and cocktails and am full of suggestions for fulfilling local experiences.  I also love animals.  I own cats and grew up with dogs.   I design my homes to be pet friendly and would love to meet your pets.  After all, your pets will be jealous if you fail to include them in your fantasy adventure.

We are always looking for new ideas, suggestions and guidance regarding our existing properties and ideas for future worlds.  Your assistance is commendable.

We understand that the true cost of a hotel includes the opportunity cost of your time and promise to work diligently to maximize your enjoyment from every second of your vacation adventure.  You'll never again be comfortable sitting on your bed at the Hilton watching infomercials.  Game on, Paris.

host_about:
I’m a moderately geeky real estate investor who prefers to be outdoors and is an avid hiker, fisher, runner and explorer. 

I live in one of my favorite places, Columbus, Ohio.  I moved here from NYC in 2014.

At Edifice, we algorithmically analyze and acquire foreclosures in qualified opportunity zones and develop those properties into vacation rentals that double as live-action guest experiences.  We work to reconceptualize residential real estate and the hotel industry, offering you the opportunity to book your own fantasy world.  Our primary goal is your satisfactory suspension of disbelief.

host_about:
Bruce and I are retired and enjoying time together and with family.  I like gardening and cooking and having friends over and we are very active in the community.  Located 1.5 miles west of the center of downtown Columbus. Easy access to all freeways and on many bus routes.

We returned to AirBNB, after a hiatus of 3 years spent building and finishing this new home  Reviews prior to 2019 are from our "Little church on the alley".We can be about as involved as guests would like - from "here you are, have a nice stay" - to cooking dinner. Guests are free to enjoy the garden and patio.

YOUR SPACE IS PRIVATE, WE HAVE SEPARATE KITCHENS. The only shared space is the few steps inside the exterior door to your entry. 

We really try to host folk who need longer stays - weeks to months, hence the 30 day minimum. Most of our guests are moving to Columbus and need a place to anchor for a while. I really want to communicate with before you book, in case for some reason this is not a good fit. We have lived here for many decades and know our way around so we often help with a wide variety of questions.
 
We have traveled quite a lot and usually stay at Airbnb sites - so much nicer than fancy hotels. 

There is a tab on Airbnb for “Accessibility” but the check off answers only cover disabilities affecting motor  issues. Our unit is downstairs, the stairs are not steep. However I am visually impaired and we have many features addressing this. Message me for more info on any disability or limitation. We are all unique!

neighborhood_overview:
The Short North is a hip, culture-rich area centered on N high Street. Contemporary galleries fill converted warehouses, and the Wexner Center for the Arts hosts boundary-pushing exhibitions. Shops selling records, streetwear, and vintage clothes galore, with student-packed coffee houses, craft-beer bars, and casual eateries.

Programming at Short North Stage spans musicals and cutting-edge drama. Enjoy endless mimosas and a boutique like brunch at Forno Kitchen and bar. Enjoy the most tasty coffee in all of Columbus at Northstar Cafe.

Enjoy a fantastic steak with fine dining to match at Hyde Park. If more low scale is your thing, but your wanting steak. Ruth's Chris is a short drive away. Maybe a gourmet burger is more your style, you can make sure to enjoy one by going to Bareburger.

Maybe in the mood for Italian? Martini Modern Italian has you covered and is less than 10 minutes away from the condo. Another amazing dinning option is The Guild House

name: Home in Columbus · ★4.63 · 3 bedrooms · 3 beds · 1 bath
neighborhood_overview: This home is located in the Historic King Lincoln neighborhood with sidewalks throughout. name: Townhouse in Columbus · ★4.82 · 3 bedrooms · 4 beds · 2.5 baths
neighborhood_overview:
Historic German Village Neighborhood, right outside of downtown Columbus. Walkable to downtown as well as shopping, coffee shops, restaurants, and bars.

Right, when you step outside our Lovely house you will be steps away from S 3rd Street. As you start to walk left you are steps away from Chapman's Eat Market, The Book Loft, Hausfrau Haven, Stauf's Coffee, Tiki Botanicals, Winans Chocolates, and many more!

The neighborhood is one mile from Mapfre Stadium, two miles from Ohio State's campus, three miles from the short north, and four miles from Downtown. Bars within a 5-minute walk from the Big Blue House include the Rambling House and Rumba Cafe. Alternatively, you can take a walk to Glen Echo Park, one of Columbus's most beautiful parks. Clintonville restaurants and shops are just a half-mile away as well.

There are 2 Free Parking Spots located in the driveway.

name: Home in Columbus · ★4.98 · 2 bedrooms · 3 beds · 1.5 baths
neighborhood_overview:
-Whetstone Park in Clintonville is a Columbus landmark and you have direct access to this park that includes bike trails, baseball fields and tennis courts, a pond, ravine, library and recreation facility, as well as the 13-acre (5.3 ha) Columbus Park of Roses. Opened in 1952, the Park of Roses is a frequent site for weddings and special events. In June, the Park of Roses hosts its annual "Rose Festival." During summer months concerts featuring many of Columbus' brass bands are held every Sunday evening at the Park's gazebo. Whetstone Park also hosts an annual Fourth of July fireworks display for the Clintonville community.
-The Clintonville Farmer’s Market has it all, from bison and sausage to certified organic fruits and vegetables. Unlike other farmer’s markets, Clintonville’s producers are mostly food based, but there are a few craft vendors here and there. Catch the market between late April and early November for one of the most lively markets in the city.

name: Rental unit in Columbus · ★4.54 · Studio · 1 bath
neighborhood_overview:
If you are looking for a true college experience then this is it! The studio is located right in the heart of The Ohio State University campus which makes for a great central location throughout Columbus.

This neighborhood is thriving with students and young adults working from their porch, walking to and from High St, lounging on the grass of their front yards, and enjoying all sorts of outdoor activities.

Walk to the nearby Newport Music Hall, South Campus of Ohio State and just a 5 minute Uber ride to all the top restaurants, great shopping and top nightlife of the lively Short North and Downtown areas.

Leave the car parked and wander over to High St just a 4 minute walk away where you will find numerous restaurants, bars, breweries, event centers, and cafes all right on your doorstep.

Columbus’ amazing food scene features top-ranked chefs, a rich farm-to-table movement, one-of-a-kind restaurants and creative artisan desserts and this ne
host_about: Providing guests with the best experience possible here in Columbus, Ohio! Being an Ohio State Buckeye has showed me how amazing this city is and now I want to share my city with you fellow travelers. From football to restaurants to conventions, Columbus is a great city to visit any time of the year! O-H

neighborhood_overview:
Historic German Village is a quaint old-line neighborhood with brick-streets on the southern edge of Downtown Columbus. Full of preserved and updated 19th-century homes, old brick and stone sidewalks, cafes, pubs, parks and more, it's a joy to stroll on foot.

Be sure to check out nearby well-known dining options like Brown Bag Deli, The Olde Mohawk, Schmidt's Sausage Haus, Lindey's, Stauf's Coffee, and Pistacia Vera.

Take a walk through Schiller Park and watch the ducks in the lake there.

Catch an Uber or use an electric scooter to visit all that Downtown Columbus has to offer!

neighborhood_overview:
This walkable, bikeable neighborhood, a short 1.5 miles from downtown Columbus and it’s major highways, is one of Columbus’ most coveted areas. A hybrid of urban flair and neighborhood warmth, Grandview’s vibes are at the same time laid-back and buzzing with energy. Stroll the wide, tree-lined sidewalks of Grandview Ave amid the hum of cafe-table chatter.

Discover specialized independent shops, curated New-York style boutiques, a chocolatier’s gorgeous handmade truffles, independent breweries, top-rated coffee roasters, cutting-edge salons, and of course, world-class restaurants that use fresh, locally-sourced ingredients. The electric mix of restaurants here have consistently been recognized by critics and diners alike for their cuisine, ambience, and outstanding attention to detail. Grandview is also home to a collection of award-winning craft microbreweries and taprooms.

A hub of creative culture and out-of-the-ordinary experiences, Grandview offers an array

By day, I’m a consultant. 
By night, I’m a friends/family man and an Ohio sports junkie. 

I’m a well traveled Airbnb guest and have pulled a lot of inspiration from other properties so I know what great hosts should do to create a comfortable guest experience. Be sure to ask me about a few of my favorite things on our welcome sheet.

Make yourself at home!

neighborhood_overview:
The neighborhood of Franklinton is currently undergoing a revitalization. Its an incredibly charming location where everyone is super friendly and a large number of the residents have lived there for decades. Some houses are undergoing renovations and are boarded up or abandoned. Like any neighborhood close to a downtown area, crime exists, but has gotten way better over the years. This particular home is right down the street from a community garden and an elementary school. There are tons of kids that live on the street and it has a wonderful sense of community. I also have two little ones and have spent lots of time at this home with zero issues.

Franklinton Fridays are a great way to explore the surrounding businesses and meet cool people in the neighborhood!

neighborhood_overview:
Franklinton is an up and coming area with rough spots (abandoned/boarded up houses) next to newly renovated homes. My street has always seemed relatively quiet and I’ve never felt unsafe here. Please do a quick Google search to make sure you’re comfortable with the area prior to booking.

FRANKLINTON HISTORY
Welcome to Franklinton, the oldest settlement of non-Indigenous settlers in Central Ohio, founded in 1797 by Lucas Sullivant on the west bank of the Scioto River, pre-dating the founding of a new state capital that would come to be known as Columbus. The land we now recognize as Franklinton, has known territory of Indigenous communities of Adena, Hopewell, and Shawandassee Tula, Wyandotte, Delaware, and Seneca.

From its start, Franklinton has been a resilient community. The town was moved further west just one year after its founding due to what would become a theme in Franklinton’s history – floodwaters. But the residents persevered and by the early 20th

neighborhood_overview:
The city’s central business, entertainment, and cultural hub, Downtown includes the Uptown, Arena, and Discovery districts. Corporate towers and theaters surround Capitol Square, anchored by the Greek Revival–style Ohio Statehouse. Brewpubs, cocktail bars, and diverse restaurants are nearby. The riverside Scioto Mile promenade leads to Bicentennial Park with its striking fountain and performing-arts pavilion.

The east side of downtown Columbus offers a dynamic blend of historic neighborhoods and modern revitalization. It's a diverse area teeming with cultural gems, local eateries, and unique entertainment venues. From the vibrant arts scene in the Discovery District to the eclectic shops and cafes of historic neighborhoods like German Village, this side of downtown Columbus pulses with energy. King-Lincoln District

The Brick Beauty CBUS is located in the King-Lincoln Bronzeville neighborhood of Columbus, which has seen continuing renovation and revitalization in recent years, and has benefited the community and its residents.

Just north of Olde Towne East, King-Lincoln District is the epicenter of the city’s African American heritage, and you’ll see that on display in murals along the Long Street Bridge. The King Arts Complex combines African American art and history with community events like free Summer Jazz Series on Thursday evenings in July and August. The Lincoln Theater is lovingly restored in its original Egyptian style, and you’ll find performances of all types gracing its stage. Support local and truly experience Columbus and the King-Lincoln District!

German Village is a charming and historic neighborhood located in the heart of Columbus, Ohio. It is known for its picturesque brick streets, quaint homes, and friendly community. name: Townhouse in Columbus · ★4.95 · 3 bedrooms · 4 beds · 1 bath
neighborhood_overview:
Our home is located in the Merion Village neighborhood which is one of the fastest growing neighborhoods in Columbus with the historic and charming German Village only a handful of blocks north. Downtown Columbus, Nationwide Children's Hospital, and the Arena District are all less than 10 minutes away.

Because we're so close to downtown, our neighborhood is definitely more urban than suburban. We live close to a firehouse, so we hear the expected sirens here and there during the week.

Merion Village is an up-and-coming neighborhood with ongoing revitalization in the area, however, you will see a few houses here and there which appear to be in an older or mid-renovation condition. Our home has the benefit of being in an area where we have very good neighbors who all look out for each other. None of our guests have experienced any sort of criminal activity in and around our home and we have exterior cameras on both sides of the house for additional peace of mind.
host_about:
Welcome! We're Claire and Matt, we got married in 2021 and this is our first home! Matt is from Northwest Ohio and has lived all over the state, attending OSU for undergrad. Claire grew up in St. Louis and attended grad school in Ohio. Since they met, she hasn't left!

We love to travel and explore beautiful locations and enjoy new cuisine and cultures. We're so excited to allow travelers to have that experience in our vibrant city!

name: Home in Columbus · ★4.99 · 2 bedrooms · 5 beds · 1.5 baths
neighborhood_overview:
Built in 1886, our traditional German house is rich in history and character, our home is truly only footsteps away from beautiful Schiller Park and walkable to all that our neighborhood, German Village, has to offer.

We encourage walks in the brick-lined neighborhood - you’ll find bookstores, pubs, coffee shops, gardens and gorgeous historical homes along the way. Or grab the picnic basket in the kitchen and head out to Schiller Park with byo-refreshments (Shakespeare in the Park happens all summer long). German Village is a unique, beautiful old neighborhood in an urban setting - it's one of a kind.
host_about:
Hi! I'm a communications professional who has been working from home for close to a decade and I immensely enjoy the benefits of WFH traveling. I especially enjoy being entrenched in the neighborhoods, which is why I love Airbnb. Having grown up in rural Ohio, I appreciate the beauty of countryside but fell in love with cityscape. I moved to Los Angeles after college, then spent years in downtown Chicago but found my way back to my home city: Columbus. I would describe myself as an urban culture-junkie, modern art lover, and amateur photographer; I enjoy music of all kinds, food, wine, coffee and I live for those experiences that broaden my perspectives and enrich my life.

When it comes to hosting, we are thrilled to host our German Village home. Built in 1886, our traditional German house is rich in history and character, truly only footsteps away from beautiful Schiller Park. We encourage walks in the brick-lined neighborhood - you’ll find bookstores, pubs, coffeeshops, gardens and gorgeous historical homes along the way. Or grab the picnic basket in the kitchen and head out to Schiller Park with byo-refreshments (Shakespeare in the Park happens all summer long). Around the corner, there is a Lyft bike station, and down the street you can access the bike path which leads to downtown and beyond - a favorite way of ours to brewery hop. Additionally, being so close to downtown and accessible to highways, you are a short Lyft/Uber ride away from Franklinton, Downtown, Short North, Old Town East, THE Ohio State campus. You can’t beat the location!

If you are more interested in the history of my ancestors settling in German Village or the history of the family who owned this home for 100+ years, don’t hesitate to reach out.  As avid travelers and lovers of new experiences, you’ll see our nod to traveling throughout the house. 

We are excited to host you and share our beautiful neighborhood and German culture! Please let us know if you have any questions or needs.

Final note- as a city-dweller mama - I strived to make this home family-friendly so we have a pack and play, high chair, baby gate, kid toys in storage on-site as well as numerous children’s books. We’ve put outlet covers in most rooms to help curb curious toddlers. If you need anything else to make your stay more comfortable while traveling with littles, don’t hesitate to reach out - we get it and are happy to help (we also love your fur babies and have several ourselves)!

neighborhood_overview: "If you’re familiar with the history of German immigration to Over-the-Rhine, then the settling of Columbus’s German Village will sound very familiar. In the mid-19th-century, fully one third of the population of Columbus was of German descent, and the community built schools, churches, businesses, and eventually, the residential neighborhood now known as German Village. It’s a dense historic district with charm to spare and---plenty of shops, restaurants, and amenities." - Cincinnati Magazine

name: Home in Columbus · ★4.85 · 1 bedroom · 1 bed · 1 bath
neighborhood_overview:
This walkable, bikeable, hip and historic neighborhood, just two miles from downtown Columbus and its major highways, is one of Columbus’ most beloved areas. A hybrid of urban flair and neighborhood warmth, Grandview’s vibe is at the same time laid-back and buzzing with energy.

Stroll the wide, tree-lined sidewalks of Grandview Avenue amid the hum of café-table chatter. Discover specialized independent shops, curated New York-style boutiques, a chocolatier’s gorgeous handmade truffles, independent breweries, top-rated coffee roasters, cutting-edge salons, and of course, world-class restaurants that use fresh, locally-sourced ingredients. The eclectic mix of restaurants here have consistently been recognized by critics and diners alike for their cuisine, ambience, and outstanding attention to detail.

Grandview is also home to a collection of award-winning craft microbreweries and taprooms. A hub of creativity, culture, and out-of-the-ordinary experiences, Grandview

This walkable, bikeable, hip and historic neighborhood, just two miles from downtown Columbus and its major highways, is one of Columbus’ most beloved areas. A hybrid of urban flair and neighborhood warmth, Grandview’s vibe is at the same time laid-back and buzzing with energy.

Stroll the wide, tree-lined sidewalks of Grandview Avenue amid the hum of café-table chatter. Discover specialized independent shops, curated New York-style boutiques, a chocolatier’s gorgeous handmade truffles, independent breweries, top-rated coffee roasters, cutting-edge salons, and of course, world-class restaurants that use fresh, locally-sourced ingredients. The eclectic mix of restaurants here have consistently been recognized by critics and diners alike for their cuisine, ambience, and outstanding attention to detail.

Grandview is also home to a collection of award-winning craft microbreweries and taprooms. A hub of creativity, culture, and out-of-the-ordinary experiences, Grandview

name: Home in Columbus · ★4.87 · 3 bedrooms · 5 beds · 1.5 baths
neighborhood_overview: "If you’re familiar with the history of German immigration to Over-the-Rhine, then the settling of Columbus’s German Village will sound very familiar. In the mid-19th-century, fully one third of the population of Columbus was of German descent, and the community built schools, churches, businesses, and eventually, the residential neighborhood now known as German Village. It’s a dense historic district with charm to spare and---plenty of shops, restaurants, and amenities." - Cincinnati Magazine

name: Home in Columbus · ★4.93 · 3 bedrooms · 3 beds · 1 bath
Home in Columbus · ★4.76 · 3 bedrooms · 3 beds · 1 bath
neighborhood_overview:
This is the old Weinland Park neighborhood which is just north of Victorian Village and the famous Short North. It is encompassed by the University District. This development boom was created in the 1930's and 1940's resulting from new streetcar lines and the blossoming of factories. Commercial and entertainment facilities are concentrated on the North High Street corridor, but also pocket the inner part of the neighborhood.
A recent flood of new investment has brought growth and revitalization to the area. Investment into the community includes the South Campus Gateway which was finished in 2005, providing retail and a new food district. Also around the corner is the Budd Dairy Food Hall and Short North District!

name: Rental unit in Columbus · ★4.75 · 1 bedroom · 1 bed · 1 bath
neighborhood_overview:
Old Town East is one of Columbus' most charming and historic neighborhoods, offering a unique mix of stunning architecture, cultural landmarks, and vibrant local businesses. With a range of local amenities and easy access to downtown Columbus, Old Town East is the perfect neighborhood for anyone looking to experience the best of the city.

First settled in the early 1800s, Old Town East boasts a rich history that can be seen in the beautifully preserved Victorian homes and stately mansions that line its streets. Visitors can take a stroll through the neighborhood to admire the architecture, or explore the historic landmarks such as the Kelton House Museum and Garden or the Ohio Theatre, which offer a glimpse into Columbus' storied past.

Old Town East is also home to a vibrant community of local businesses, with a variety of restaurants, cafes, and shops within walking distance of your space. Grab a coffee and a pastry at the nearby Winstons Coffee and Waffles, or e
host_about:
Hello!

Thank you for staying with us!  We look forward to hosting you.

Codi (my sister) and I have lived here for the past 3 years and have been hosting on Airbnb since 2017 which means you'll get high service and quality, local recommendations (especially if you love food and coffee as much as I do!)

Feel free to book or message us first, we are happy to answer any specific questions in advance.

I recently left the Army after a 10 year career that took me all over the world to pursue being a full time entrepreneur!  My "preneur" is building an Airbnb and real estate business with my sister Codi.  Codi is a full time recruiter for finance and hospitality positions for Goodwin Recruiting.  She handles all the messaging on airbnb so you will most likely be speaking to her.

I am well traveled and have a uniquely high cleanliness standard for all of our units (thanks to the Army).  I know what a host should do to create a comfortable, clean and safe experience and I'd like to prove it to you!

Be sure to ask about the best bars and restaurants in Columbus.  We know quite a few bar and restaurant owners and can definitely give you the best local recommendations and would love to help you enjoy Columbus in anyway we can!

name: Rental unit in Columbus · ★5.0 · 1 bedroom · 1 bed · 1 bath
neighborhood_overview:
BEST NEIGHBORHOOD FOR 2023!!! GRANDVIEW HEIGHTS! Very walkable and easily accessible to all freeways. Just minutes west of downtown but embodying both small-town and urban vibes, the Grandview community is close-knit and friendly, and people of all ages and walks of life call this walkable area home. Grandview is a neighborhood that has something for everyone! neighborhood_overview:
German Village is a historic neighborhood just south of downtown Columbus, OH. Initially platted in 1814 in Columbus' South End, German Village was generally developed between years 1840 and 1914. It was settled largely by German immigrants in the mid-1800s. German descendants at one time comprised as much as one-third of the population of Columbus. Restoration began in 1959 and the Historic District was established in 1963. German Village was the FIRST historic district in the U.S. and it remains a model for all that came after. In the year 1974, German Village joined the Historic Register. Today, more than 1,600 preservations have been completed.

Walk everywhere - sidewalks are wide - people are warm - parks and restaurants are plentiful! And German Village is central to everything in Columbus.

Also visit Tiki Botanicals on S. 3rd St or our in-unit Tiki Botanicals pop-up shop! Use code HAUS10 to shop in-person and online.

name: Home in Columbus · ★4.96 · 2 bedrooms · 2 beds · 1.5 baths
neighborhood_overview:
Just south of downtown Columbus lies German Village, one of the most idyllic neighborhoods in the country. Built by German settlers hundreds of years ago, the area is defined by its brick homes and shops, as well as brick-lined streets. Historic charm and modern tweaks exist side by side here.

Peruse local businesses that include delicious pastry and coffee shops, the truly unique 32-room Book Loft , free Shakespeare at the neighborhood’s Schiller Park and beautiful holiday lights and markets during the winter.

German Village became a city historic district in 1960 and was added to the National Register of Historic Places in 1974, becoming the list's largest privately funded preservation district.

neighborhood_overview:
The King-Lincoln neighborhood is bound by Broad Street to the South, 20th Street to the East, Atcheson Street to the North, and I-71 to the West. It is a neighborhood within the Near East side and is surrounded by downtown Columbus, Old Towne East, and the Mount Vernon neighborhood.

The city’s central business, entertainment, and cultural hub, Downtown includes the Uptown, Arena, and Discovery districts. Corporate towers and theaters surround Capitol Square, anchored by the Greek Revival–style Ohio Statehouse. Brewpubs, cocktail bars, and diverse restaurants are nearby. The riverside Scioto Mile promenade leads to Bicentennial Park with its striking fountain and performing-arts pavilion.

name: Townhouse in Columbus · ★4.81 · 3 bedrooms · 3 beds · 1.5 baths
neighborhood_overview: German Village is a historic neighborhood in Columbus, Ohio, just south of the city's downtown. It was settled in the early-to-mid-19th century by a large number of German immigrants, who at one time comprised as much as a third of the city's entire population. It became a city historic district in 1960 and was added to the National Register of Historic Places in 1974, becoming the list's largest privately funded preservation district, and in 2007, was made a Preserve America Community by the federal government. The area is defined by its brick homes and shops, as well as brick-lined streets. Historic charm and modern tweaks exist side by side here. Peruse local businesses that include delicious pastry and coffee shops, the truly unique 32-room Book Loft , free Shakespeare at the neighborhood’s Schiller Park and beautiful holiday lights and markets during the winter.

neighborhood_overview:
Old Town East is one of Columbus' most charming and historic neighborhoods, offering a unique mix of stunning architecture, cultural landmarks, and vibrant local businesses. With a range of local amenities and easy access to downtown Columbus, Old Town East is the perfect neighborhood for anyone looking to experience the best of the city.

First settled in the early 1800s, Old Town East boasts a rich history that can be seen in the beautifully preserved Victorian homes and stately mansions that line its streets. Visitors can take a stroll through the neighborhood to admire the architecture, or explore the historic landmarks such as the Kelton House Museum and Garden or the Ohio Theatre, which offer a glimpse into Columbus' storied past.

Franklinton is an up and coming area with rough spots (abandoned/boarded up houses) next to newly renovated homes. My street has always seemed relatively quiet and I’ve never felt unsafe here. Please do a quick Goo.gle search to make sure you’re comfortable with the area prior to booking.

FRANKLINTON HISTORY
Welcome to Franklinton, the oldest settlement of non-Indigenous settlers in Central Ohio, founded in 1797 by Lucas Sullivant on the west bank of the Scioto River, pre-dating the founding of a new state capital that would come to be known as Columbus. The land we now recognize as Franklinton, has known territory of Indigenous communities of Adena, Hopewell, and Shawandassee Tula, Wyandotte, Delaware, and Seneca.

From its start, Franklinton has been a resilient community. The town was moved further west just one year after its founding due to what would become a theme in Franklinton’s history – floodwaters. But the residents persevered and by the early 20t
