name: Rental unit in Columbus · ★4.44 · Studio · 1 bed · 1 bath
neighborhood_overview: If you are looking for a true college experience then this is it! The studio is located right in the heart of The Ohio State University campus which makes for a great central location throughout Columbus.  This neighborhood is thriving with students and young adults working from their porch, walking to and from High St, lounging on the grass of their front yards, and enjoying all sorts of outdoor activities.   Walk to the nearby Newport Music Hall, South Campus of Ohio State and just a 5 minute Uber ride to all the top restaurants, great shopping and top nightlife of the lively Short North and Downtown areas.   Leave the car parked and wander over to High St just a 4 minute walk away where you will find numerous restaurants, bars, breweries, event centers, and cafes all right on your doorstep.  Columbus’ amazing food scene features top-ranked chefs, a rich farm-to-table movement, one-of-a-kind restaurants and creative artisan desserts and this neighborhood is no exception.  Grab a bite
host_about: Providing guests with the best experience possible here in Columbus, Ohio! Being an Ohio State Buckeye has showed me how amazing this city is and now I want to share my city with you fellow travelers. From football to restaurants to conventions, Columbus is a great city to visit any time of the year! O-H

At its heart, the Short North is an arts neighborhood, as evidenced by the many murals along the sides of the buildings. Beyond that, it’s a hub of activity offering more than 100 restaurants, breweries, galleries and boutiques and booming with new mixed-use and residential development.

The district itself is confined to one block on either side of High Street, with Victorian Village to the west and Italian Village to the right.

host_about:
Hi! I’m Wendy. I love being a host in my beautiful hometown city of Columbus, Ohio! My passions are traveling, dancing, watching sports, and making joyful moments with my family and friends. The main reason my husband and I started this business together was so we could provide a great experience for guests to make beautiful memories of their own.  We LOVE to travel and we hope you do too!

As physical and mental health advocates, we understand research that states positive memory retrieval reduces stress levels and calms physiological stress responses. So get out and explore life with each other in our fun and comfortably curated properties and locals! We take pride in our city and would like people from all over the world to enjoy it as much as we do. When we’re not tending to other philanthropic or entrepreneurial pursuits, we are learning, loving, and growing with our three children, and our Australian Labradoodle.

Please make yourself at home at any of properties in the area whether you are looking to experience condo life near the lively atmosphere of downtown Columbus, the Short North, the Arena District, Ohio State University, a quiet single-family neighborhood home, or our 8-person sleeping RV, or fun water and sun (or snow) at our waterfront lake house on Buckeye Lake! 

Our detailed guidebooks are loaded with restaurants, bars, and things to do in the area, but don’t hesitate to reach out for any local recommendations. Start building your beautiful memories today! Go Buckeyes...and Go Bobcats!

German Village is an enchanting, historical neighborhood in Columbus, OH with old-fashioned cobblestone streets and gas lamps on houses. German Village is a walkable district with several coffeeshops, restaurants, and bars to check out. There are a few parks in the area to explore, which comes in handy if you have a dog or children who need space to play.

You'll definitely want to check out The Book Loft, a sprawling book shop of 32 rooms full of nooks and crannies to get lost in. There are several boutiques spread about German Village, which will make exploring the neighborhood all the more rewarding. Schiller Park encompasses a few blocks of the neighborhood and is a favorite among dog owners all across the city- you might even catch a live show of Shakespeare in the Park. And a statue of Gambrinus, the patron saint of beer, is a great photo op and is not far from the AirBnB.

host_about:
I’m a moderately geeky real estate investor who prefers to be outdoors and is an avid hiker, fisher, runner and explorer. 

I live in one of my favorite places, Columbus, Ohio.  I moved here from NYC in 2014.

At Edifice, we algorithmically analyze and acquire foreclosures in qualified opportunity zones and develop those properties into vacation rentals that double as live-action guest experiences.  We work to reconceptualize residential real estate and the hotel industry, offering you the opportunity to book your own fantasy world.  Our primary goal is your satisfactory suspension of disbelief.  

We encourage you to raise the question:  why stay in a hotel room when I could otherwise rule from the pinnacles of King's Landing or Caesar's Palace, escape 1,000 leagues under the sea, wage my own wizard battle, establish a new dynasty at Pi-Ramesses, lead my lion pack into the Serengeti, cross swords with Hook in my pirate fortress, or cast down dragons in my own lair?  

I love great food and cocktails and am full of suggestions for fulfilling local experiences.  I also love animals.  I own cats and grew up with dogs.   I design my homes to be pet friendly and would love to meet your pets.  After all, your pets will be jealous if you fail to include them in your fantasy adventure.

We are always looking for new ideas, suggestions and guidance regarding our existing properties and ideas for future worlds.  Your assistance is commendable.

We understand that the true cost of a hotel includes the opportunity cost of your time and promise to work diligently to maximize your enjoyment from every second of your vacation adventure.  You'll never again be comfortable sitting on your bed at the Hilton watching infomercials.  Game on, Paris.

neighborhood_overview:
Our neighborhood Franklinton is situated just west of Downtown Columbus, and is full of historic homes. This neighborhood has experienced many phases through out it's existence, and is currently in a revitalization phase. There are lots of properties being renovated, and some that still remain boarded and empty. This area has experienced some crime in the past, but has improved in recent years.

Franklinton has experienced several great floods in the past, and has been somewhat neglected throughout the middle to late part of the 1900's. The Franklinton Floodwall, completed in 2004, is 7 miles long, cost $134 million. The wall's completion has released the area from being considered a floodplain, as well as releasing the previous building restrictions that often prevented development in the past. As a result, commercial and industrial activities are starting to grow in the Franklinton Area.

name: Home in Columbus · ★4.96 · 1 bedroom · 2 beds · 1 bath
neighborhood_overview:
German Village is a historic neighborhood just south of downtown Columbus, OH. Initially platted in 1814 in Columbus' South End, German Village was generally developed between years 1840 and 1914. It was settled largely by German immigrants in the mid-1800s. German descendants at one time comprised as much as one-third of the population of Columbus. Restoration began in 1959 and the Historic District was established in 1963. German Village was the FIRST historic district in the U.S. and it remains a model for all that came after. In the year 1974, German Village joined the Historic Register. Today, more than 1,600 preservations have been completed.

Walk everywhere - sidewalks are wide - people are warm - parks and restaurants are plentiful! And German Village is central to everything.

name: Home in Columbus · ★4.75 · 4 bedrooms · 4 beds · 3.5 baths
neighborhood_overview:
Goodale Park is surrounded by Victorian Village, a cluster of homes with charming architectural features. It is the oldest park in Columbus and among the oldest in the United States.

Although Goodale Park contains an expansive playground and tennis courts, the park's main attraction is its view of the Columbus skyline and the serenity offered alongside a scenic pond and the charm of the gazebo and of its historic park shelter. A walk through Goodale Park is a refreshing experience.

Nightlife abounds in the Short North all year round and Gallery Hop on the first Saturday of the month is a must see! Pizza and sausage stalls set up near St. John the Baptist Church (located just steps from the front door) during fall’s Columbus Italian Festival. Craft breweries and pubs are close by on N. 4th Street. This is a beautiful neighborhood full of history and new traditions to explore!

neighborhood_overview:
The King-Lincoln neighborhood, also known as Bronzeville, is a historic district located in the Near East Side of Columbus, Ohio. It is named after two prominent African American figures: Martin Luther King Jr. and Abraham Lincoln. The area was once a thriving center of African American culture and commerce, particularly during the mid-20th century.

The King-Lincoln district was originally developed in the late 19th century as a streetcar suburb for Columbus' wealthy citizens. However, by the mid-20th century, it had become a predominantly African American neighborhood due to the discriminatory housing practices of the time. Despite this, the community flourished, and King-Lincoln became a hub of African American music, art, and culture. Notable figures who frequented the neighborhood include Duke Ellington, Lena Horne, and Sammy Davis Jr.

In recent years, the King-Lincoln neighborhood has undergone significant redevelopment efforts to preserve its historic charac

neighborhood_overview:
Our neighborhood Franklinton is situated just west of Downtown Columbus, and is full of historic homes. This neighborhood has experienced many phases through out it's existence, and is currently in a revitalization phase. There are lots of properties being renovated, and some that still remain boarded and empty. This area has experienced some crime in the past, but has improved in recent years.

Franklinton has experienced several great floods in the past, and has been somewhat neglected throughout the middle to late part of the 1900's. The Franklinton Floodwall, completed in 2004, is 7 miles long, cost $134 million. The wall's completion has released the area from being considered a floodplain, as well as releasing the previous building restrictions that often prevented development in the past. As a result, commercial and industrial activities are starting to grow in the Franklinton Area.

neighborhood_overview:
Harrison West is a central neighborhood in the Short North, nestled between Victorian Village and Grandview. The neighborhood is just a few blocks from Goodale Park and all of the dining, shopping, and nightlife of the Short North. It's also conveniently within walking distance from the heart of the Ohio State University campus. The brick streets, quiet evenings, and tree canopies make you forget that you're just a few blocks from all of Columbus' main hustle and bustle.

This historic urban neighborhood is located just a 3 minute drive from downtown Columbus, Ohio. It sits on several blocks along the Olentangy River and includes the western part of the Near Northside Historic District, which was placed on the National Register of Historic Places in 1975.

For my favorite neighborhood recommendations, check out the "Historic Harrison West - the Heart of Columbus" Guidebook!

name: Home in Columbus · ★4.94 · 3 bedrooms · 3 beds · 1.5 baths
neighborhood_overview:
Olde Towne East is located in the historical Near East Side of Columbus, Ohio. It is one of Columbus’ oldest neighborhoods. Nestled between Downtown, Bexley, and Driving Park, Olde Towne East has over 1,000 homes, some as old as the 1830s, and more than 50 architectural styles including Italianate, Queen Anne and Victorian.

These homes were built by many of the famous individuals of Columbus including industrialists, lawyers, judges, teachers, architects, mayors, governors, and legislators, many of which shaped Columbus.

Today, people of all colors, backgrounds, lifestyles, and incomes make up Olde Towne East. The neighborhood is much sought after for its housing stock and convenience to everything Columbus has to offer.

host_about:
Hi! I’m Wendy. I love being a host in my beautiful hometown city of Columbus, Ohio! My passions are traveling, dancing, watching sports, and making joyful moments with my family and friends. The main reason my husband and I started this business together was so we could provide a great experience for guests to make beautiful memories of their own.  We LOVE to travel and we hope you do too!

As physical and mental health advocates, we understand research that states positive memory retrieval reduces stress levels and calms physiological stress responses. So get out and explore life with each other in our fun and comfortably curated properties and locals! We take pride in our city and would like people from all over the world to enjoy it as much as we do. When we’re not tending to other philanthropic or entrepreneurial pursuits, we are learning, loving, and growing with our three children, and our Australian Labradoodle.

Please make yourself at home at any of properties in the area whether you are looking to experience condo life near the lively atmosphere of downtown Columbus, the Short North, the Arena District, Ohio State University, a quiet single-family neighborhood home, or our 8-person sleeping RV, or fun water and sun (or snow) at our waterfront lake house on Buckeye Lake! 

Our detailed guidebooks are loaded with restaurants, bars, and things to do in the area, but don’t hesitate to reach out for any local recommendations. Start building your beautiful memories today! Go Buckeyes...and Go Bobcats!

name: Townhouse in Columbus · ★4.89 · 1 bedroom · 2 beds · 1 bath
neighborhood_overview: Welcome to Olde Towne East, a neighborhood that seamlessly blends historic charm with modern vibrancy. Located in Columbus, Ohio, Olde Towne East is known for its rich architectural heritage, diverse community, and thriving arts and culture scene. As you stroll through the tree-lined streets of Olde Towne East, you'll be captivated by the stunning Victorian-era homes that grace the area. These majestic residences, adorned with intricate details and ornate facades, stand as a testament to the neighborhood's history and character. Many of these historic homes have been lovingly restored and maintained, adding to the neighborhood's allure. The community itself is a melting pot of different cultures, with a diverse population that fosters a sense of inclusivity and warmth. Residents of Olde Towne East take pride in their neighborhood, and a strong sense of community can be felt in the air. Whether it's the friendly greetings of neighbors or the lively conversations at local gathering spots

neighborhood_overview:
Old Town East is one of Columbus' most charming and historic neighborhoods, offering a unique mix of stunning architecture, cultural landmarks, and vibrant local businesses. With a range of local amenities and easy access to downtown Columbus, Old Town East is the perfect neighborhood for anyone looking to experience the best of the city.

First settled in the early 1800s, Old Town East boasts a rich history that can be seen in the beautifully preserved Victorian homes and stately mansions that line its streets. Visitors can take a stroll through the neighborhood to admire the architecture, or explore the historic landmarks such as the Kelton House Museum and Garden or the Ohio Theatre, which offer a glimpse into Columbus' storied past.

neighborhood_overview:
For family, friends and visitors, German Village is also a home away from home. That’s because you don’t have to live in German Village to feel like you belong here. Whether you are interested in community services, historic preservation and architecture, neighborhood events, or where to shop and dine, German Village has something for everybody.

UNIQUE URBAN DESIGN
A highway bridge over Interstate 70 is all that separates the German Village Historic District from downtown Columbus, but as one looks east from the interstate, the difference between old and new is glaring. A 20+ story structure sits just north of the interstate bridge, and just south, in German Village, no structure is higher than three stories. Five blocks south, the spire of St. Mary Church stands 197’ off the sidewalk and towers over everything around it. Structures and sidewalks are orange masonry, and many streets (about half) are still brick pavers.

name: Rental unit in Columbus · ★4.95 · 1 bedroom · 1 bed · 1 bath
neighborhood_overview: Just south of downtown lies German Village, one of the most idyllic neighborhoods in the country. Built by German settlers years ago, the area is defined by its gorgeous turn of the century homes and quaint shops, as well as brick lined streets. Historic charm and modern tweaks exist side by side here. Peruse local businesses that include pastry and coffee shops, unique restaurants and taverns and the truly unique 32-room Book Loft, free Shakespeare at the neighborhood’s Schiller Park. Not to mention the beautiful holiday lights and markets during the winter.
host_about: Hi, I'm Jeni, your fearless hostess. Once upon a time, I painted this little neighborhood of German Village red. Now my days are spent running after toddlers, high five-ing middle schoolers at hockey practice and serving up some of the best lunch in downtown Columbus. I am delighted by entertaining regulars and telling an out-of-towner where the best places to go are when they are visiting this city. As a life long explorer and lover of dive bars, I always seek out all the best joints no matter the neighborhood. I'm here to tell you how to enjoy Columbus as a local, feel right at home and enjoy your stay with us.

name: Condo in Columbus · ★5.0 · 3 bedrooms · 5 beds · 2 baths
neighborhood_overview: Welcome to German Village, one of the most picturesque areas in America, located just south of the heart of Columbus. As a neighborhood constructed by immigrants in the 1800s, German Village exudes a unique charm that seamlessly blends historic allure with modern updates. You'll be delighted by the beautiful brick homes and streets that adorn this easy-going locality. As your host, I am thrilled to introduce you to the enchanting and fascinating world of German Village. Get ready for an unforgettable experience!
host_about:
Hello all and welcome!

I am originally from India where we believe in heartfelt hospitality we pay the highest regard to our guests and value hospitality. In fact, I live by the popular Indian saying, “Atithi Devo Bhava,” which means that the guest is God’s own reflection.

With that in mind, I founded Nice N Neat Homes to help people with hosting their properties as short-term rentals.

I moved to Ohio over 13 years ago from Miami, Fl, and have been working in the commercial real estate field ever since. 

I am an explorer and I find it really enlighting to visit new places and learn about local cultures.

Every guest is the most important visitor on our properties and I strive to create personal experiences for our guests that they will treasure for a lifetime.

The district includes the section of East Broad Street from Ohio Avenue on the west to Monypenny Street on the east. It includes lavish residences and is also home to Franklin Park Conservatory.

Franklin Park Conservatory and Botanical Gardens is Central Ohio’s premier botanical garden and home to the iconic John F. Wolfe Palm House which dates back to 1895. Situated just east of Franklin Park, the Conservatory is approximately two miles from downtown Columbus. Our house is located within walking distance to the Conservatory.

For family, friends and visitors, German Village is also a home away from home. That’s because you don’t have to live in German Village to feel like you belong here. Whether you are interested in community services, historic preservation and architecture, neighborhood events, or where to shop and dine, German Village has something for everybody.

UNIQUE URBAN DESIGN
A highway bridge over Interstate 70 is all that separates the German Village Historic District from downtown Columbus, but as one looks east from the interstate, the difference between old and new is glaring. A 20+ story structure sits just north of the interstate bridge, and just south, in German Village, no structure is higher than three stories. Five blocks south, the spire of St. Mary Church stands 197’ off the sidewalk and towers over everything around it. Structures and sidewalks are orange masonry, and many streets (about half) are still brick pavers.

neighborhood_overview:
Located between downtown Columbus and Bexley, the East Broad Street Historic District in Columbus, Ohio is a historic district that was listed on the National Register of Historic Places in 1987. The district includes the section of East Broad Street from Ohio Avenue on the west to Monypenny Street on the east. It includes lavish residences and is also home to Franklin Park Conservatory.

Franklin Park Conservatory and Botanical Gardens is Central Ohio’s premier botanical garden and home to the iconic John F. Wolfe Palm House which dates back to 1895. Situated just east of Franklin Park, the Conservatory is approximately two miles from downtown Columbus. Our house is located within walking distance to the Conservatory.

The apartment is located in the heart of Downtown Columbus within the historic Merion Village neighborhood.

Merion Village is just a short walk from the Scioto River, with multiple parks lying along the river’s edge as part of the Scioto Mile. This 175-acre parkland features a free outdoor climbing wall and an Audubon center frequented by nature enthusiasts. Pedestrian and bike paths within the Mile provide a welcome respite from the hustle and bustle of the city.

Find yourself dining at the many cafes that surround the area along Thurman Avenue, Parsons Avenue and the popular High St with all the cuisines of the world just a short walk in either direction.

name: Home in Columbus · ★4.54 · 1 bedroom · 2 beds · 1.5 baths
neighborhood_overview:
Our neighborhood Franklinton is situated just west of Downtown Columbus, and is full of historic homes. This neighborhood has experienced many phases through out it's existence, and is currently in a revitalization phase. There are lots of properties being renovated, and some that still remain boarded and empty. This area has experienced some crime in the past, but has improved in recent years.

Franklinton has experienced several great floods in the past, and has been somewhat neglected throughout the middle to late part of the 1900's. The Franklinton Floodwall, completed in 2004, is 7 miles long, cost $134 million. The wall's completion has released the area from being considered a floodplain, as well as releasing the previous building restrictions that often prevented development in the past. As a result, commercial and industrial activities are starting to grow in the Franklinton Area.

neighborhood_overview: Old North Columbus is a neighborhood located just north of the Ohio State University in Columbus, Ohio. It was founded in 1847 where, at the time, it was a stand-alone city out of the confines of Columbus until it was incorporated into the City of Columbus in 1871. In its early years the city was a popular stagecoach stop with people traveling from Worthington to Columbus. Today Old North Columbus is popular for its local music and its unique "untouched architecture" which is reminiscent of its old roots.

name: Rental unit in Columbus · ★4.95 · 4 bedrooms · 4 beds · 2 baths
neighborhood_overview:
Victorian Village, nestled in the heart of Columbus, Ohio, is a neighborhood steeped in rich history and timeless charm. Originally developed in the late 19th century, this residential area showcases a remarkable collection of meticulously restored Victorian-era homes. The district's architectural beauty, characterized by intricate details and ornate facades, will transport you to a bygone era.

Throughout the years, Victorian Village has evolved into a vibrant community that balances preservation with contemporary living. The neighborhood's commitment to historic preservation is evident in its tree-lined streets, meticulously manicured gardens, and preservation of the original charm. Residents and visitors alike are treated to a captivating blend of historic architecture and modern amenities.

Victorian Village's character extends beyond its architecture, as it embodies a strong sense of community. Its residents are proud custodians of the area's heritage, fosterin

host_about:
I’m a moderately geeky real estate investor who prefers to be outdoors and is an avid hiker, fisher, runner and explorer. 

I live in one of my favorite places, Columbus, Ohio.  I moved here from NYC in 2014.

At Edifice, we algorithmically analyze and acquire foreclosures in qualified opportunity zones and develop those properties into vacation rentals that double as live-action guest experiences.  We work to reconceptualize residential real estate and the hotel industry, offering you the opportunity to book your own fantasy world.  Our primary goal is your satisfactory suspension of disbelief.  

We encourage you to raise the question:  why stay in a hotel room when I could otherwise rule from the pinnacles of King's Landing or Caesar's Palace, escape 1,000 leagues under the sea, wage my own wizard battle, establish a new dynasty at Pi-Ramesses, lead my lion pack into the Serengeti, cross swords with Hook in my pirate fortress, or cast down dragons in my own lair?  

I love great food and cocktails and am full of suggestions for fulfilling local experiences.  I also love animals.  I own cats and grew up with dogs.   I design my homes to be pet friendly and would love to meet your pets.  After all, your pets will be jealous if you fail to include them in your fantasy adventure.

We are always looking for new ideas, suggestions and guidance regarding our existing properties and ideas for future worlds.  Your assistance is commendable.

We understand that the true cost of a hotel includes the opportunity cost of your time and promise to work diligently to maximize your enjoyment from every second of your vacation adventure.  You'll never again be comfortable sitting on your bed at the Hilton watching infomercials.  Game on, Paris.

FRANKLINTON NEIGHBORHOOD: Franklinton is a mix of quiet residential streets and a revitalized industrial area with galleries and event spaces in old factory buildings. Victorian Village, nestled in the heart of Columbus, Ohio, is a neighborhood steeped in rich history and timeless charm. Originally developed in the late 19th century, this residential area showcases a remarkable collection of meticulously restored Victorian-era homes. The district's architectural beauty, characterized by intricate details and ornate facades, will transport you to a bygone era.

Throughout the years, Victorian Village has evolved into a vibrant community that balances preservation with contemporary living. The neighborhood's commitment to historic preservation is evident in its tree-lined streets, meticulously manicured gardens, and preservation of the original charm. Residents and visitors alike are treated to a captivating blend of historic architecture and modern amenities.

The apartment is located in the heart of Downtown Columbus within the historic Merion Village neighborhood.

Merion Village is just a short walk from the Scioto River, with multiple parks lying along the river’s edge as part of the Scioto Mile. This 175-acre parkland features a free outdoor climbing wall and an Audubon center frequented by nature enthusiasts. Pedestrian and bike paths within the Mile provide a welcome respite from the hustle and bustle of the city.

Find yourself dining at the many cafes that surround the area along Thurman Avenue, Parsons Avenue and the popular High St with all the cuisines of the world just a short walk in either direction.

neighborhood_overview: Old North Columbus is a neighborhood located just north of the Ohio State University in Columbus, Ohio. It was founded in 1847 where, at the time, it was a stand-alone city out of the confines of Columbus until it was incorporated into the City of Columbus in 1871. In its early years the city was a popular stagecoach stop with people traveling from Worthington to Columbus. Today Old North Columbus is popular for its local music and its unique "untouched architecture" which is reminiscent of its old roots.

name: Rental unit in Columbus · ★5.0 · Studio · 4 beds · 1.5 baths
neighborhood_overview:
German Village is a historic neighborhood just south of downtown Columbus, OH. Initially platted in 1814 in Columbus' South End, German Village was generally developed between years 1840 and 1914. It was settled largely by German immigrants in the mid-1800s. German descendants at one time comprised as much as one-third of the population of Columbus. Restoration began in 1959 and the Historic District was established in 1963. German Village was the FIRST historic district in the U.S. and it remains a model for all that came after. In the year 1974, German Village joined the Historic Register. Today, more than 1,600 preservations have been completed.

Walk everywhere - sidewalks are wide - people are warm - parks and restaurants are plentiful! And German Village is central to everything in Columbus.

Also visit Tiki Botanicals on S. 3rd St or our in-unit Tiki Botanicals pop-up shop! Use code HAUS10 to shop in-person and online.

name: Home in Columbus · 3 bedrooms · 3 beds · 1.5 baths
neighborhood_overview: The Columbus neighborhood of Clintonville is located just south of Worthington and north of Ohio State’s University District, situated on the north-central side of Columbus. Historically, Clintonville has been the home of Columbus’ first zoo (in operating for just four short months in 1905) and Olentangy Park, an amusement park once boasted as the largest in the U.S. Present-day destinations in Clintonville are much more understated but equally as notable. Popular vinyl record stores like Elizabeth’s Records and vegan hotspots like Portia’s Cafe and Pattycake Bakery have made Clintonville one of the hottest hipster neighborhoods in the U.S, while the Park of Roses continues to be seen as one of the best parks in Columbus.

neighborhood_overview: Old North Columbus is a neighborhood located just north of the Ohio State University in Columbus, Ohio. It was founded in 1847 where, at the time, it was a stand-alone city out of the confines of Columbus until it was incorporated into the City of Columbus in 1871. In its early years the city was a popular stagecoach stop with people traveling from Worthington to Columbus. Today Old North Columbus is popular for its local music and its unique "untouched architecture" which is reminiscent of its old roots.

name: Home in Columbus · 5 bedrooms · 6 beds · 2 baths
neighborhood_overview:
This charming yet eclectic home in an affluent, urban neighborhood supplies guests with easy access to entertainment all from within the confines of a quaint, family-friendly, neighborhood. We love the Clintonville area in Columbus, and would be happy to assist you with any recommendations you should need during your visit.

Where to go? : One thing I love about this house is how close you are to the freeway and yet accessible by walking to some amazing spots in Clintonville such as:

Flowers and Bread - a unique local bakery/cafe that also does flower arranging classes!

Coffee: Flowers and Bread, or Starbucks just a few more blocks!

Restaurants: To many to list them all but we love Northstar Cafe, Hot Chicken Takeover, Rusty Bucket, and Local Cantina!

Other Activities: The Columbus Park of Roses - One of Columbus's largest metro parks, and a beautiful rose garden that is an icon of the area.

Don't miss the bike/walking

neighborhood_overview:
Named one of the ‘Best Hometowns’ by Ohio Magazine, Gahanna offers 750+ acres of parkland, vibrant neighborhoods, opportunities for business growth and more! Rich in heritage and diversity, Gahanna offers a friendly environment, unique historic attractions, high-quality restaurants and accommodations, eclectic shopping destinations and expansive green space.

Only eight miles from downtown Columbus and minutes away from John Glenn International Airport, Gahanna is a choice location for business and leisure. With a strong emphasis on community, family and fun, Gahanna offers a wide variety of seasonal and special events.

Discover Creekside Park—complete with waterfalls, paddleboat and nearly a dozen great restaurants. Visit the Ohio Herb Center, tour a winery, attend premier events and more!

neighborhood_overview: German Village is memorable for a thousand reasons, all of which are intimately personal to the individuals fortunate to reside in or visit the neighborhood. The sense of community is palpable, the historic architecture is beautiful, and the history is visible. German Village is not easily forgotten. From walkability to a great sense of community, German Village is an incredible place to be. You feel it when you cross through the Third Street gateway or explore the parks. Millions of individual bricks were placed on top of one another to form this Village.
host_about:
I'm a professional photographer splitting my time between Columbus, Manhattan, and Barcelona. My wife and I travel all over the country and world, now with our two little boys. We're Superhosts ourselves, which make us very courteous guests and will always leave your place tidy upon our departure, just as we’d hope you’d treat our home.  

Check out our listings if you’re interested in staying at one of our properties in Columbus. From a stunning 3 bedroom Mid-century modern home in Bexley to turn of the century historic brick homes in the heart of German Village. You're covered on your next trip to Columbus whether looking for a weekend retreat, a relaxing place to call home during a business trip, attending a convention, a wedding, or in need of longer-term accommodations for your medical residency or stint as a professor at OSU!
We look forward to hosting you!

name: Rental unit in Columbus · ★New · Studio · 1 bed · 1 bath
neighborhood_overview: If you are looking for a true college experience then this is it! The studio is located right in the heart of The Ohio State University campus which makes for a great central location throughout Columbus.  This neighborhood is thriving with students and young adults working from their porch, walking to and from High St, lounging on the grass of their front yards, and enjoying all sorts of outdoor activities.   Walk to the nearby Newport Music Hall, South Campus of Ohio State and just a 5 minute Uber ride to all the top restaurants, great shopping and top nightlife of the lively Short North and Downtown areas.   Leave the car parked and wander over to High St just a 4 minute walk away where you will find numerous restaurants, bars, breweries, event centers, and cafes all right on your doorstep.  Columbus’ amazing food scene features top-ranked chefs, a rich farm-to-table movement, one-of-a-kind restaurants and creative artisan desserts and this neighborhood is no exception.  Grab a bite

neighborhood_overview:
Goodale Park is surrounded by Victorian Village, a cluster of homes with charming architectural features. It is the oldest park in Columbus and among the oldest in the United States.

Although Goodale Park contains an expansive playground and tennis courts, the park's main attraction is its view of the Columbus skyline and the serenity offered alongside a scenic pond and the charm of the gazebo and of its historic park shelter. A walk through Goodale Park is a refreshing experience.

host_about:
I’m a moderately geeky real estate investor who prefers to be outdoors and is an avid hiker, fisher, runner and explorer. 

I live in one of my favorite places, Columbus, Ohio.  I moved here from NYC in 2014.

At Edifice, we algorithmically analyze and acquire foreclosures in qualified opportunity zones and develop those properties into vacation rentals that double as live-action guest experiences.  We work to reconceptualize residential real estate and the hotel industry, offering you the opportunity to book your own fantasy world.  Our primary goal is your satisfactory suspension of disbelief.  

We encourage you to raise the question:  why stay in a hotel room when I could otherwise rule from the pinnacles of King's Landing or Caesar's Palace, escape 1,000 leagues under the sea, wage my own wizard battle, establish a new dynasty at Pi-Ramesses, lead my lion pack into the Serengeti, cross swords with Hook in my pirate fortress, or cast down dragons in my own lair?  

I love great food and cocktails and am full of suggestions for fulfilling local experiences.  I also love animals.  I own cats and grew up with dogs.   I design my homes to be pet friendly and would love to meet your pets.  After all, your pets will be jealous if you fail to include them in your fantasy adventure.

We are always looking for new ideas, suggestions and guidance regarding our existing properties and ideas for future worlds.  Your assistance is commendable.

We understand that the true cost of a hotel includes the opportunity cost of your time and promise to work diligently to maximize your enjoyment from every second of your vacation adventure.  You'll never again be comfortable sitting on your bed at the Hilton watching infomercials.  Game on, Paris.

name: Home in Columbus · ★5.0 · 3 bedrooms · 4 beds · 2.5 baths
neighborhood_overview:
German Village is a picturesque historic neighborhood in Columbus, Ohio, known for its cobblestone streets, well-preserved 19th-century brick homes, and rich German heritage. It offers a unique blend of old-world charm and modern amenities, making it a popular destination for tourists.

Schiller Park, located in the heart of German Village, is a beautiful urban park with lush green spaces, a picturesque pond, and walking paths. Visitors can relax in its serene surroundings, have a picnic, or simply enjoy the peaceful atmosphere. The park often hosts community events and festivals, adding to its vibrant atmosphere.

Together, German Village and Schiller Park provide a captivating experience, offering a glimpse into the city's history, culture, and natural beauty, making them must-visit destinations for travelers exploring Columbus.

neighborhood_overview:
Clintonville is a quirky neighborhood just north of OSU's campus. We have many wonderful restaurants and bars within walking distance. If you want recommendations, don't hesitate to ask! There is also a fun locally owned theater called Studio 35 that usually has some random throwback movie showing, as well as the most recent movies. Make sure to check it out! Just a short walk up the street in both directions are several antique malls and curated co-ops with multiple vendors. The Little Light Collective is a favorite and just up the road from Studio 35.

If you're here during the summer months, make sure you don't miss out on Clintonville's Farmer's Market. Lots of locally grown produce and other products as well as musicians and coffee!

If you like to feel like you are in the city but have space to forget, our cottage is perfect. We're in the middle of a fun and eclectic area, with easy access to green space and a quiet walk in the woods.

name: Home in Columbus · ★New · 5 bedrooms · 5 beds · 2.5 baths
neighborhood_overview: Old North Columbus is a neighborhood located just north of the Ohio State University in Columbus, Ohio. It was founded in 1847 where, at the time, it was a stand-alone city out of the confines of Columbus until it was incorporated into the City of Columbus in 1871. In its early years the city was a popular stagecoach stop with people traveling from Worthington to Columbus. Today Old North Columbus is popular for its local music and its unique "untouched architecture" which is reminiscent of its old roots.

We are across the street from Cameron Mitchell's Food Hall with multiple incredible dining options. Just 10 min north of downtown Columbus and a few minutes to the interstate.

name: Home in Columbus · ★New · 2 bedrooms · 1 bath
neighborhood_overview:
A Vibrant Gem in Columbus' Historic Heart

Nestled in a charming historic district south of downtown Columbus, this delightful neighborhood offers a unique blend of urban convenience and small-town charm. Just steps away from your rental on Southwood Avenue, you'll find tree-lined streets adorned with Victorian-era homes, offering glimpses into the city's rich past.

Around the corner, vibrant local cafes and bistros beckon with tempting aromas, while independent shops and boutiques line the avenues, showcasing an eclectic mix of treasures. Art galleries and studios add a touch of bohemian flair, and cozy pubs with friendly faces invite you to linger over a craft beer or two.

For a taste of outdoor living, head to the nearby park, where lush greenery and walking paths provide a welcome escape from the city buzz. Here, you can enjoy a leisurely picnic under the shade of mature trees, toss a frisbee with friends, or simply soak up the sunshine.
